`crates/steno/src` is the whole compiler crate: `.steno` source text in, Plover JSON dictionaries and LSP snippet artifacts out. `lib.rs` declares the module tree and is the only place that states the pipeline order — `parse` → `expand` → (`render` | `snippet` | `blocks`) — and it is strictly one-way; no stage reads back from a later one. Everything under this directory either produces AST for that pipeline (`parse/`), transforms it (`expand/`, `stroke/`), consumes it into an artifact (`render/`, `snippet/`, `blocks.rs`), or supports all of the above (`error.rs`, `json_out.rs`, `editor/`). File I/O is deliberately absent from the library — only `bin/`'s three binaries write to disk, driving the library purely through its re-exported functions.

Two small files at this level are load-bearing across nearly every subtree. `error.rs` defines the five typed errors (`StenoError`, `StrokeError`, `ExpandError`, `RenderError`, `SnippetError`) that `parse/`, `expand/`, `render/`, and `snippet/` all return instead of panicking; `StenoError::line()`'s 1-based numbering is fed by `parse/`'s fence/directive line tracking and must not be off-by-one adjusted by any consumer. `json_out.rs`'s `OrderedMap`/`to_json` is the deterministic serializer that `render/` and `snippet/` both funnel their output through — insertion order there is dictionary output order, and neither subtree may substitute a different map type without breaking diff-stability.

`stroke/` (`parse_stroke`/`render_stroke`/`KeySet`/count-bank arithmetic) is consumed by `expand/` (count/repeat resolution) and by `render/`'s per-entry stroke handling; all stroke text must go through `stroke/`'s API rather than being string-spliced anywhere else in the crate. `editor/`'s `Event`/`Behaviors`/`interpret`/`serialize` surface is the shared keystroke IR consumed by `render/` (`PLAIN`/`SMART` profile dispatch), `snippet/` (tabstop placement), and `blocks.rs` (`@literal` block navigation) — a change to what `PLAIN`/`SMART`/`SMART_INDENT` mean in `editor/` silently changes output in all three without any corresponding edit there. `parse/` is the sole producer of `Entry`/`Chunk`/`Expr`; every later stage matches its `Chunk` variants exactly as `parse/` defines them, so a new template operator requires coordinated edits in `parse/` and whichever of `expand/`/`render/`/`blocks.rs` needs to handle the new variant.

`bin/` sits outside the library and depends only on the re-exported pipeline functions and types listed in `lib.rs`; it uses stringly-typed errors internally rather than the typed hierarchy in `error.rs`, and all three binaries independently hardcode the workspace-root-resolution logic that `lib.rs` has no opinion on.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence to report.